Create a separate <strong>list of references</strong> at the end of your document that provides more information about each of the sources cited in your writing.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The list of references at the end of your document provides more detail about Kuchar's book in an entry that reads Kuchar, comma, M period 2000 in parentheses period, Kuchars, Kitchens, and Kuchan, New York, New York, Skyscraper Publishing.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"4"},"leftText":"<p>In your family history, you used some information from an author named Paula Baker.<br /><br />Family members reading your work will see an in-text citation in parentheses. This tells them where you found your information.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">From your family history:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">A typical rider for the Pony&nbsp;Express was less than 21 years old and did not have a family <span class=\"marker\">(Baker, 2013)</span>.</span></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":0,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"5"},"rightText":"<p style=\"padding-left:20px;text-indent:-20px;line-height:2;\">&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span class=\"marker\">&nbsp;</span></p>","leftText":"<p>Next, they can look for the corresponding References entry.</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":0,"showNext":0,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":true},"leftText":"<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><p style=\"padding-left:20px;text-indent:-20px;line-height:2;text-align:center;\">References</p><p style=\"padding-left:20px;text-indent:-20px;line-height:2;\"><span class=\"marker\">Baker, P. (2013, November)</span>. History of the Pony Express. <em>US News, 11(</em>1), 1-5. Retrieved from<br />http://www.usnews.com/opinion/articles/2013/11/04/history-of-pony-express</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","rightText":null},{"settings":{"showAudio":0,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0},"leftText":"<p>This provides additional information about the source material you used from Paula Baker, with enough detail so that your readers can identify and retrieve it for themselves.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":null},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0,"audioPath":"6"},"leftText":"<p>As you write and use the words and ideas of others to support your own ideas, include an in-text citation for each source.<br /><br />Make a note of the citation as you add it so that you know you need to include a corresponding entry in your list of references.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"For example, your family history includes a direct quotation from page 3 of an article by Paula Baker written in 2013.  You make a note of this on your in-text citation list as Baker comma 2013.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":"In-text citations:  The basics"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"7"},"leftText":"<p>Enclose in-text citations in parentheses and include the following information:</p><ul style=\"padding-left:15px;\"><li>last&nbsp;name of the author followed by a comma</li><li>year of publication</li><li>page number for a direct quotation, or paragraph number if no page number is available</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-powertip\" style=\"width:90%;\"><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\">Did you know?</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>APA style emphasizes the date of publication.<br /><br />When your reader is reading your work, he or she will be able to note immediately when your sources published their work.&nbsp; This is especially important in fields in which current information is valued.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"In the in-text citation, open parenthesis, Baker, 2013, p period 2, close parenthesis, Baker is the last name of the author, 2013 is the year of publication, and p period 2 is the page number that you need for a direct quotation. You use a paragraph number if no page number is available.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"8"},"leftText":"<p>Place in-text citations at the end of the sentence or set of sentences from the source they are citing.&nbsp; Always put the citation <strong>before</strong> the period so it is part of the sentence.<br /><br />When you <strong>paraphrase</strong> or <strong>summarize,</strong> include the last name of the author and the year of publication in the in-text citation.<br /><br />When you use a <strong>direct quotation</strong>, also include a page number using the abbreviation <strong>p</strong>.<br /><br />If no page number is available, include a paragraph number using the abbreviation <strong>para</strong>.&nbsp; To find the paragraph number, count the paragraphs by hand.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Paraphrase or summary:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width: 100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">A typical rider for the Pony&nbsp;Express was less than 21 years old and did not have a family <span class=\"marker\">(Baker, 2013)</span>.</span></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br /><br /><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Direct quotation:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">Pony Express riders were a unique group of young men, &rdquo;unafraid to take on a challenge and willing to push themselves to the limit&quot; <span class=\"marker\">(Baker, 2013, p. 2)</span>.</span></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"9"},"leftText":"<p>Sometimes you may include the&nbsp;author&#39;s name at the beginning of a sentence to let your reader know when you are borrowing his or her words and ideas.<br /><br />This is also considered citing and is called a <strong>signal phrase</strong>.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Signal phrase:&nbsp;</span><span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\"> In this example,&nbsp; the signal phrase is: Baker tells.</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\"><span class=\"marker\">Baker tells</span> of the extreme conditions under which the Pony Express riders worked, &quot;sometimes traveling through dust storms, thunderstorms, and snow.&quot;</span></td></tr></tbody></table>","headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"10"},"leftText":"<p>When you use a signal phrase, you do not need to put the author&#39;s last name in parentheses.&nbsp; Instead, place the date in parentheses immediately after the author&#39;s name.<br /><br />If you use a signal phrase with a direct quotation, then place the date immediately after the author&#39;s name AND place the page or paragraph number after the quotation, but before the period at the end of the sentence.<br /><br />If you use a signal phrase more than once, then include the date in parentheses only the first time you mention the source.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">In-text citation for a signal phrase:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width: 100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\"><span class=\"marker\">Baker (2013)</span> believes that there will never again be a team of workers as dedicated as were the men of the Pony Express.</span></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br /><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Page or paragraph added for a direct quotation:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" height=\"70\" width=\"422\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\"><span class=\"marker\">Baker (2013)</span> tells of the extreme conditions under which the Pony Express riders worked, &quot;sometimes traveling through dust storms, thunderstorms, and snow&quot; <span class=\"marker\">(p. 3)</span>.</span></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br /><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Signal phrase used more than once:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width: 100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\"><span class=\"marker\">Andrews (2016)</span> states that the riders who served as part of the Pony Express were paid very little for their services.&nbsp; <span class=\"marker\">Andrews</span> also mentions that a typical rider rode approximately 75 miles a day before stopping to rest for the night.&nbsp;</span></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0,"audioPath":"11"},"leftText":"<p>One of the paragraphs in your family history includes a long direct quotation from horticulturalist Ellen Rivas.&nbsp; For quotations longer than 40 words, APA has special formatting requirements:<br />&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"padding-left: 15px;\"><li>Introduce the quotation with a signal phrase.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>Do not use quotation marks.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>Indent the quotation a half- inch from the left margin.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>Place the period before the parentheses that contain the page or paragraph number.</li></ul>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Signal phrase for direct quotation longer than 40 words:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain ju-tight\" style=\"width: 100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><p><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">Horticulturalist Ellen Rivas (2016), a native of southwest Florida, explains how dangerous the introduction of non-native plant species into an environment can be:</span></p><p style=\"padding-left:2em;\"><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">The introduction of non-native species to the welcoming biome represented in southwest Florida poses a real danger to native flora and fauna. When a transplanted species is placed in its new environment, growth may go unchecked in the absence of insect enemies or meteorological factors that previously kept the growth of the species in balance. (para. 4)</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"12"},"leftText":"<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-powertip\" style=\"width:90%;\"><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\">ASK YOURSELF:&nbsp; Deciding how to format a citation<span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">&nbsp;,</span></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Did I use a paraphrase or summary? </strong></p><ul style=\"padding-left:15px;\"><li>Include the author&#39;s last name and date of publication in parentheses at the end of the sentence.</li></ul><p><strong>Did I use a direct quotation?</strong> &nbsp;</p><ul style=\"padding-left:15px;\"><li>Enclose the author&#39;s words in quotation marks&nbsp;</li><li>Include a page or paragraph number in addition to the author&#39;s last name and date of publication.&nbsp;</li><li>If your quotation is longer than 40 words, then indent it one-half inch instead of using quotation marks.</li></ul><p><strong>Did I use a signal phrase?</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"padding-left:15px;\"><li>Put the year in parentheses after the first mention of the author&#39;s name.</li></ul><p><strong>Did my signal phrase introduce a direct quotation?</strong>&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"padding-left:15px;\"><li>Add a page or paragraph number in parentheses after the direct quotation.</li></ul><p><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"/images/picture_it.png\" style=\"width: 27px; height: 27px;\" />&nbsp; <a href=\"S3_BUCKET_/JCS100/4/AskYourself_Formattingacitation.pdf\" onclick=\"window.open(this.href, '', 'resizable=no,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=yes,dependent=yes,width=826,left=100,height=750,top=50'); return false;\">Ask yourself: Deciding how to format a citation, Picture it!</a>&nbsp; <a href=\"S3_BUCKET_/JCS100/4/Screen_reader_ask_yourself_formatting_a_citation.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/images/accessible_icon.png\" style=\"width: 17px; height: 20px;\" /><span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Screen reader version of Ask yourself: Deciding how to format a citation, opens in a new tab</span></a>&nbsp;</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>","rightText":null},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"13"},"leftText":"<p>What do you do if your source has no author?</p><ul style=\"padding-left:15px;\"><li>Use a shortened version of the title or the full title, if it is short.</li><li>Capitalize all key words in the title.</li><li>If it is an article title, then place it inside quotation marks.&nbsp;</li><li>If it is a book title, then italicize it.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</li></ul><table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-powertip\" style=\"width:100%;\"><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\">Careful!</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><p>Many online articles actually <strong>do</strong> have authors.&nbsp; Look closely at the entire page; make sure you scroll down to the bottom the page if you do not see an author near the top of the article.&nbsp;</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Source with unknown author</span>:</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">Pony Express riders even were subjected to attacks by the Paiute Indian tribe in Nevada during the Paiute War of 1860&nbsp;<span class=\"marker\">(&quot;Pony Express Basic Facts,&quot; 2016)</span>.</span></td></tr></tbody></table>","headerText":"In-text citations:  Missing information, images, and multiple sources"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0,"audioPath":"14"},"leftText":"<p>What do you do if your source has no date?<br /><br />Use n.d. in place of the year of publication.<br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /> See the mini-lesson <em>Finding citation and reference details</em> if you are having trouble finding the information you need for your citations!</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Source with no date:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">Marchers traveled to the capital by all manner of transportation&mdash;some covering hundreds of miles to make it from cities like Milwaukee and St. Louis<span class=\"marker\"> (Porter, n.d.).</span></span></td></tr></tbody></table>","headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0,"audioPath":"15"},"leftText":"<p>Do you need to provide citations for photographs and other images?<br /><br />Images such as photographs or drawings are considered <strong>figures</strong>.&nbsp; When you use figures in your work include a <strong>caption</strong> beneath the figure.<br /><br />Create a caption as follows:</p><ol style=\"padding-left:15px;\"><li>Start with the word Figure followed by a number and a period that shows the order of the image in your work.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</li><li>Follow this with the figure title and a period. Capitalize only the first word and proper nouns in the title.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>After the title, include a brief explanation of the figure.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>End with an in-text citation that includes the creator&#39;s last name and year of publication in parentheses.<br />&nbsp;</li></ol>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/images/image.png\" style=\"width: 20px; height: 14px;\" /> <span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Image with caption:</span></p><p><img alt=\"A photograph shows a picnic area by a lake.  The caption starts with a figure number, Figure 1.  It continues with the title of the photograph, which is Lake Stone picnic area.  This is followed by a brief explanation, which is &quot;our family has been meeting here for the past 70 years.&quot;  It ends with an in-text citation that includes the author's last name and the year of publication in parentheses.  Gorski, 2016.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0,"audioPath":"16"},"rightText":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/images/image.png\" style=\"width: 20px; height: 14px;\" /> <span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Image with unknown author:</span></p><p><img alt=\"A photograph of a lake house with a caption.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /><br /><span class=\"marker\">Figure 3.&nbsp; Lake house at sunset.&nbsp; This shows the author&#39;s house at the time of the ant invasion (2013).</span></p>","leftText":"<p>What if the image has no author?<br /><br />Make sure that the caption includes the image title and only the year of publication in parentheses.<br />&nbsp;</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"17"},"leftText":"<p>One of your paragraphs about the Pony Express riders has information from more than one source!<br /><br />Place each in-text citation directly after the information it supports.<br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" />See the mini-lesson <em>Including many sources in a paragraph</em> for more information.</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">More than one source:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width: 100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><p><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">We have conflicting information about how long Pony Express riders stayed on the job. &quot;Many riders served for the entire year and a half that the Pony Express was in business&quot; <span class=\"marker\">(Baker, 2013, p. 3)</span>. Others tell us that the difficult nature of the work contributed to a high dropout rate with many riders only spending a few weeks in employment <span class=\"marker\">(&quot;Pony Express Basic Facts,&quot; 2016)</span>.</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"18"},"leftText":"<p>There are many different types of sources that you might use in your writing: videos, works with multiple authors, or even works with no title!<br /><br />If you are not sure how to format an in-text citation, then use the <strong>JUICE APA style quick reference</strong> or another online resource such as the <strong>Purdue Online Writing Lab guide</strong>.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">In-text citation formatting information:</span></p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/images/picture_it.png\" style=\"width: 27px; height: 27px;\" /><a href=\"S3_BUCKET_/JCS100/4/JUICEAPAstylequickreference.pdf\" onclick=\"window.open(this.href, '', 'resizable=no,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=no,dependent=yes,width=825,left=100,height=750,top=50'); return false;\">JUICE APA style quick reference</a>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"margin-left:2em;\"><a href=\"https://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/560/02/\" target=\"_blank\">Purdue Online Writing Lab--In-Text Citations: The Basics <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">(opens in a new window)</span></a>&nbsp;</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"19"},"leftText":"<p>For each source included in an in-text citation in your document, you need to include an entry on a separate <strong>list of references</strong> at the end of your document, unless it is a personal communication such as an interview or email that cannot be retrieved.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"For example, the body of your family history includes the sentence &quot;Stefan and Anna Kuchar arrived at Ellis Island in the winter of 1898&quot; followed by Kuchar comma 2000 in parentheses. Documenting your sources<span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">&nbsp;,</span></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><ul style=\"padding-left:15px;\"><li>Give credit to a source in the body of your work by including an in-text citation enclosed in parentheses or by using a&nbsp;signal phrase.&nbsp; Include a page number in your citation if you have used a direct quote.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>Create a list of references titled References on a separate page at the end of your work.&nbsp; List each source you cited in the body of your work, except for personal communications.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>Follow citation and reference list entry formatting directions for each type of source.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</li><li>First ask yourself what type of source you have cited, and then use the&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"/images/picture_it.png\" style=\"width: 27px; height: 27px;\" /> <a href=\"S3_BUCKET_/JCS100/4/JUICEAPAstylequickreference.pdf\" onclick=\"window.open(this.href, '', 'resizable=no,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=no,dependent=yes,width=825,left=100,height=750,top=50'); return false;\">JUICE APA style quick reference</a> or a resource such as the <a href=\"https://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/560/01/\" target=\"_blank\">Purdue Online Writing Lab guide <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">(opens in a new window)</span></a> to find formatting details.</li></ul></td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>","rightText":null,"headerText":"Putting it all together"}],"overviewHeader":"Overview"}
